## Endpoint reference

| Method | Path | Notes |
|--------|------|-------|
| `GET` | `/healthz` | Returns `{status, uptime_seconds, timestamp}` — always `200` |
| `GET` | `/users/<user_id>/profile` | `200` with user object; `404` if ID unknown |
| `GET` | `/orders/recent` | Last 24 h, newest first. Optional `?limit=N` (default 20, max 100); `400` on bad value |

### Example responses

**`GET /healthz`**
```json
{"status": "ok", "uptime_seconds": 4.2, "timestamp": "2026-04-30T07:14:00+00:00"}
```

**`GET /users/1/profile`**
```json
{"id": "1", "name": "Alice Example", "email": "alice@example.com", "role": "admin"}
```

**`GET /orders/recent?limit=1`**
```json
{
  "orders": [{"id": "101", "user_id": "1", "item": "Widget A", "total": 19.99, "created_at": "..."}],
  "count": 1,
  "since": "2026-04-29T07:14:00+00:00"
}
```

Only `flask` is required — `flask-sqlalchemy` is not needed until you wire up a real database. The in-memory `USERS` and `ORDERS` dicts/lists are drop-in placeholders you can swap for ORM queries later without touching the route logic.
